DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 15-Jul-22):
> A clean full-length nrITS consensus sequence of two reads was obtained from this voucher by Dr. Kudzma. There are no ambiguities or heterogeneity; it’s a single haplotype. The sequence was deposited in GenBank.
> This sequence is 99.4-100% similar to accessions labeled as Imleria badia from North America (NA), as per the BLASTn results. In contrast to these, ITS sequences of I. badia from Europe have a face value similarity of 98-99% (for some reason this used to be one of the most commonly sequenced bolete, with hundreds of accessions from Europe). Why “face value” similarity? A MUSCLE alignment of the present sequence with a typical one from Europe is shown in Fig. 1. There is a curious 10-character deletion in the ITS2 region of the European sequence found in a few randomly sampled GenBank accessions from Europe and it is presumed to be the defining feature of the Old World genotype. Counting it in, the similarity drops from 98.83% to 96.85% (17 mismatching positions).
The ITS and TEF-1 sequences of I. badia from both sides of the Atlantic show a clear-cut phylogeographic pattern (see Fig. 2 & Fig. 3). This phenomenon is also observed in a couple of other boletes, e.g. Leccinum holopus.1 Published research on the phylogeny of Imleria doesn’t support elevation of the NA I. badia to a new species.2,3 Farid et al. (2020) write: “Based on ITS sequences, our results indicate that eastern North American I. badia form a weakly supported monophyletic clade distinct from a strongly supported clade of Eurasian sequences. These findings agree with those found by Zhu et al. (2014). This intraspecific divergence is likely due to geographic isolation (Zhu et al. 2014), and we are unaware of any reliable morphological differences.”
References:
1 Den Bakker et al., Phylogeographic patterns in Leccinum sect. Scabra and the status of the acrtic-alpine species L. rotundifoliae; Mycological Research 111: 663-672 (2007)
2 Farid et al., Expansion of the genus Imleria in North America to include Imleria floridana, sp. nov., and Imleria pallida, comb. nov.; Mycologia 112(2): 423-437 (2020)
3 Yang et al., The genus Imleria (Boletaceae) in East Asia; Phytotaxa 191(1): 081098 (2014)

Primer registro de esta especie para el pas, determinado el 5/06/2016 por Chivat Teodoro y Arias Camila, en el Humedal La Conejera Bogot, Colombia.

Basidioma estipitado, lignicola, principalmente gregario, en ocasiones solitario o cespitado, no higrofano, el Pleo mide entre 5 a 7 cm de dimetro, hemisfrico en un principio, luego pasa a ser plano convexo con el centro umbonado, orbicular (vista apical). Margen recto, entero y ligeramente ondulado, de superficie glabra, viscida y brillosa, que luego pasa a ser seca y opaca, de color rojo que tiende a oscurecerse hacia el borde, con escamas fasciculadas originadas por restos del velo universal que forma un crculo a modo de collar cerca del borde. Himenio con lamelas y lamlulas, se encuentran prximas entre s (apretadas), adnadas a ligeramente uncinadas, anchas, de borde liso, lamlulas atenuadas, de color caf claro principio, despus gris violceo y finalmente prpura negruzco, arista entera, blanquecina. Contexto homegeneo y hueco. Esporada de color marron oscuro.

Estpite de 4-8 cm de largo x 0.4-0.5 cm de ancho, cilndrico, central, sub-bulboso y con tomento basal con cordones miceliares (rizomorfos), de color blanco con zonas de color naranja rojizo que se intensifica con el tiempo, pruinoso. Se engrosa ligeramente hacia la base. De consistencia fibrosa. Sin olor o sabor apreciable. Basidiosporas elipsoidales, lisas, de paredes gruesas, con poro germinal.

A Muscle alignment of Amanita sp. sp-N46 RET 319-5 MN820545 with sequences of five AZ collections that are genetically similar appear to indicate that there are two closely related AZ groupsan idea supported by the phylogenetic tree. RET reviewed my alignment and made the following comment: Hence, Group 1 may be interpreted as having only one column treated as a MAYBE difference. With more data you could build a
case for identity; however, I think you have a very good case for two SNPs which
could be treated as no problem for arguing for a single species.
I plan to voucher and sequence more of these. From the alignment it appears that both ITS and LSU are helpful in distinguishing between Group 1/A. sp-N46 and Group 2. A sequence from RETs A. nishidae material would be helpful as well: http://www.amanitaceae.org/?Amanita%20nishidae If subject is in fact A. nishidae then A. nishidae is genetically close and possibly conspecific with A. sp-N46.
